  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions spans several decades and has evolved significantly. Here's an overview of key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a concept in response to organized crime activities in the 1920s and 1930s\n- Initially focused on concealing proceeds from illegal activities like bootlegging and gambling\n\n2. Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - United States:\n- First comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global problem\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - U.S.\n- Anti-Drug Abuse Act (1988) - Criminalized money laundering\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Expanded AML regulations post-9/11\n\n5. Global Expansion:\n- Increasing international cooperation\n- Development of comprehensive regulatory frameworks\n- Enhanced cross-border information sharing\n\nThese developments reflect a progressive approach to addressing financial crime.",
